Let \( n \) be the number of statements and let \( a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_n \) represent the sequence numbers of the true statements. Determine the sequence number(s) of the true statement(s) in the following propositions:
① When a prism is intersected by a plane, the resulting two parts are not necessarily prisms;
② A geometric solid with two parallel faces and all other faces being parallelograms is called a prism;
③ A polyhedron with one face being a polygon and all other faces being triangles is always a pyramid;
④ The intersection line of a spherical surface and a plane is always a circle when the distance from the sphere's center to the plane is less than the sphere's radius.
A: ①④
B: ②③④
C: ①②③
D: ①②③④

